But, when the audience doesn't give anything more than very basic "I like it" or "I don't like it" without going into detail, it leaves you with nothing to go on. You don't know what to improve on or not.
I don't care about encouragement.

Pretty much this, and also simply that writing is a fucking pain in the ass if you're taking it seriously. I blew thirty to forty hours of my life on the Dare sequel, and I ended up throwing away all but what I wrote in the last ten. It's easy to start something and then lose interest as it gets more challenging to stick with. I'm certainly guilty of that with Degeneracy Pressure, though I would like to get back to it. That story got plenty of attention too.
At least in my case, there seems to be something of a honeymoon phase with stories. Progress is fast and easy for the first fifty pages or so but it always seems to fade, even if I still know right where I want to take it. Afterward, it's really discipline and a sense of obligation to readers and/or characters that gets me through it. I get why people don't stick with it, especially when they have anything better to do. Writing can be done pretty casually, but it still involves a lot of honest work when all is said and done.
